# 4-Digit 7-Segment + 74HC595 + Arduino Mega (Multiplexed)

## What this build is
This project drives a 4-digit 7-segment LED display (5641AS) using:
- 1 × 74HC595 shift register to control the 8 segment lines (A..G + DP)
- 4 Arduino pins to select which digit is active (DIG1..DIG4)
- Software multiplexing to display 4 digits using shared segment wires

## Why we use a 74HC595
A 4-digit 7-segment display needs up to 8 segment control lines (A,B,C,D,E,F,G,DP).
Instead of using 8 Arduino pins, the 74HC595 lets us send those 8 bits using only 3 Arduino pins:

- DATA  (DS)   : the bit stream
- CLOCK (SHCP) : shifts bits into the chip
- LATCH (STCP) : copies the shifted bits to the output pins all at once

So: 3 pins from Arduino -> 8 outputs to segments.

## Critical 74HC595 pins (must be wired correctly)
- VCC (pin 16) must be +5V
- GND (pin 8) must be GND
- MR / SRCLR (pin 10) must be tied HIGH (+5V) or the chip stays reset
- OE (pin 13) must be tied LOW (GND) or outputs are disabled

If MR/OE are wrong or floating you’ll see "random segments" or nothing.

## Multiplexing: how 4 digits share the same segment wires
All 4 digits share the segment pins A..G and DP.
Only one digit is turned on at a time, very quickly:

1. Turn all digits OFF
2. Output segment pattern for the digit you want (via 74HC595)
3. Turn ON exactly one digit (DIG1..DIG4)
4. Wait a tiny time (hundreds to a couple thousand microseconds)
5. Repeat for the next digit

If this repeats fast enough (typically > 100 refreshes/sec), your eyes see all 4 digits continuously.

## Digit select is ACTIVE LOW
In this wiring, a digit turns on when its DIG pin is grounded.
So in code:
- HIGH = digit OFF
- LOW  = digit ON

This is why the code always does:
- set all digits HIGH (off)
- set one digit LOW (on)

## Current limiting resistors
Each segment LED must have a series resistor.
We use 220Ω per segment line between the 74HC595 output and the display segment pin.
Without resistors, the LEDs can be overdriven and the 74HC595 can be damaged.

## Segment bit order (standard table used)
The segment table encodes digits 0-9 into a byte:
- bit0 = A
- bit1 = B
- bit2 = C
- bit3 = D
- bit4 = E
- bit5 = F
- bit6 = G
- bit7 = DP

We confirmed the wiring matches this bit order by running single-bit tests.

## Common troubleshooting
### Nothing lights at all
- Check 74HC595 pin13 (OE) is GND
- Check 74HC595 pin10 (MR) is +5V
- Check digit enable: at least one DIG pin must go LOW at some point
- Verify LATCH pin: MEGA D9 -> 74HC595 pin12

### A particular digit never lights
- Verify the digit select wire for that DIG pin (and that it matches your code’s pin mapping)

### A particular segment never lights
- Check that segment’s 220Ω resistor and that the jumper is in the same breadboard row as the resistor leg
- Confirm the segment pin number on the display matches the wiring doc

### “Random” segments or unstable patterns
- Latch (STCP) not wired or wrong pin on the 74HC595
- OE/MR floating
- Breadboard row off-by-one on any of the 74HC595 pins

